					<head>Hagiographa</head>
					<msContents class=" lccn.loc.gov/n80008481" rend="visible">
						<summary>The Hagiographa, provided with vowel-points and accents.</summary>
						<textLang mainLang="he">Hebrew</textLang>
						<msItem n="0" rend="" class="lccn.loc.gov/n80008481">
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Ketuvim </title>
							<title xml:lang="he">כתובים  </title>
							<locus from="1r" to="259v"/>
							<filiation>This manuscript, though later in date, shows some points of likeness to Additional 21161 (<ref target="Margoliouth_1965" type="number">116</ref>), and also to the so-called Reuchlin Codex 3, Karlsruhe - Badische Landesbibliothek (<ref target="Karlsruhe_1892" type="number">3</ref>).</filiation>
							<note>
								<p>Folio 1r: a list of Hebrew works, probably the property of a former owner of the manuscript, comprising biblical texts, commentaries on the Bible, portions of the Talmud, and Maḥzorim.</p>
								<p>Folio 258v: a list of Sabbath lessons and a number of kabbalistic recipes.</p>
								<p>Folio 259r: a record of birth of a daughter, inscribed with the previous owner's name, Moshe Shevaḥ, with a date of 15 July <date calendar="Hebrew">222 </date>(<date calendar="Gregorian">1462</date>).</p>
							</note>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="1v" to="61r"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Psalms</title>
								<note>
									<p>Psalm 47, initially omitted, is written in the margin on folio 19r. </p>
									<p>Psalms 1-88 were numbered by the original scribe, and the rest by a later hand. </p>
								</note>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="61v" to="79r"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Daniel</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="79r" to="108v"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Ezra</title>
								<note>
									<p>Nehemiah starts on folio 91r.</p>
								</note>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="109r" to="112v"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Song of Songs</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="112v" to="116r"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Ruth</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="116r" to="120v"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Lamentations</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="120v" to="128v"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Ecclesiastes</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="128v" to="137v"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Esther</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="137v" to="162v"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Job</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="162v" to="184r"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Proverbs</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="184r" to="257v"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Chronicles</title>
								<note>
									<p>2Chronicles starts on folio 217r. Missing chapters 3:16-4:1. </p>
									<p>Some other lacunae supplied in the margin.</p>
								</note>
							</msItem>
						</msItem>
					</msContents>
					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Parchment codex of the 13th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<support>Parchment codex.</support>
								<extent>259 folios<dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>280</height>
										<width>220</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>197</height>
										<width>147</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>259 folios  (+ 2 unfoliated paper flyleaves at the beginning and at the end).</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p> 	Quires mostly of 8 leaves each.</p>
								</collation>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="2" ruledLines="23" writtenLines="21">
									<p>Uniform layout. </p>
									<p>Ruling with hard-point on the hair side of the folio is visible. </p>
									<p>Daniel and Proverbs begin a new column, and Song of Songs opens a new leaf.</p>
									<p>The first word of Daniel, Ezra-Nehemiah, Ecclesiaistes and Proverbs, and the first two of Lamentations, Esther and Chronicles are written in larger letters.</p>
									<p>The centre mark occurs in all the books except in Lamentations, Esther and Chronicles.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="1">
							<summary>Ashkenazi square script, punctuated and accentuated, of the 13th century.</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="major"/>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>Folio 1r contains a list of Hebrew works, probably the property of a formwer owner of the manuscript. </p>
							<p>Folio 258v contains a list of Sabbath lessons mainly from the Bible. Lower down there are some kabbalistic recipes. </p>
							<p>Folio 259r - a record of birth of a daughter, dated 15 July <date calendar="Hebrew">222 </date>(<date calendar="Gregorian">1462</date>). </p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="owner">Moshe Shevaḥ ben Yaʿaḳov</name>, <name type="person" role="owner">Yaʿaḳov ben Eliyah</name>, <name type="person" role="owner">Shabtai ben Yaʿaḳov</name>, previous owners, inscribed with their names on folio 258r. </p>
						</additions>
						<bindingDesc>
							<binding>
								<p>Post-1600, Harleian binding of gold-tooled red leather.</p>
							</binding>
						</bindingDesc>
					</physDesc>
					<history rend="visible">
						<origin notBefore="1200" notAfter="1299"/>
						<provenance>
							<p>
								<name type="place">Germany</name>
							</p>
						</provenance>
						<acquisition>
							<date>1753</date>
							<p>The Harley Collection, formed by <name type="person" role="owner">Robert Harley</name> (b. 1661, d. 1724), 1st earl of Oxford and Mortimer, politician, and <name type="person" role="owner">Edward Harley</name> (b. 1689, d. 1741), 2nd earl of Oxford and Mortimer, book collector and patron of the arts; inscription by Harley's librarian, <name type="person">Humfrey Wanley</name>, <date calendar="Gregorian">11 March 1723/4</date> (folio <locus n="259v"/>). Edward Harley bequeathed the library to his widow, <name type="person" role="owner">Henrietta Cavendish, née Holles</name> (b. 1694, d. 1755) during her lifetime and thereafter to their daughter, <name type="person" role="owner">Margaret Cavendish Bentinck</name> (b. 1715, d. 1785), duchess of Portland; the manuscripts were sold by the Countess and the Duchess in <date calendar="Gregorian">1753 </date>to the nation for £10,000 (a fraction of their contemporary value) under the Act of Parliament that also established the British Museum; the Harley manuscripts form one of the foundation collections of the British Library.</p>
						</acquisition>
					</history>
